First, let's find the symmetric difference of sets A and B (A △ B). The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

A = {2, 4, 6, 8}
B = {3, 6, 9}

Intersection of A and B (A ∩ B) = {6}
A △ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B) = {2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9} - {6} = {2, 3, 4, 8, 9}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (A △ B) and {6, 9, 12, 15}.

(A △ B) = {2, 3, 4, 8, 9}
C = {6, 9, 12, 15}

Intersection of (A △ B) and C ((A △ B) ∩ C) = {9}
(A △ B) △ C = ((A △ B) ∪ C) - ((A △ B) ∩ C) = {2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9, 12, 15} - {9} = {2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 12, 15}

So, (A △ B) △ {6, 9, 12, 15} = {2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 12, 15}.
